<article>
    <h1>Zoe Tay&#x2019;s wax fig&#xAD;ure gets a fresh look</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201023/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-23"><time>2020-10-23</time></a>
        - <span>TRENDING LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Jan Lee jan&#xAD;lee@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>Sin­ga­pore TV ac­tress Zoe Tay got an up­dated wax fig­ure (both right) at Madame Tus­sauds Sin­ga­pore yes­ter­day.</p>
    <p>The 52-year-old’s fig­ure was first cre­ated in 2014 for the grand open­ing of the Sen­tosa at­trac­tion. It was then clad in a luxe yel­low gown Tay wore to the 2013 Star Awards cer­e­mony.</p>
    <p>Now, her wax twin is wear­ing a black Ver­sace gown with a slit up to the thigh, which Tay wore last year to the fi­nals of the tal­ent com­pe­ti­tion Star Search.</p>
    <p>The ac­tress wrote of her restyled fig­ure in a post on In­sta­gram: “We chose this clas­sic, time­less look. So happy to see my­self again – it feels fa­mil­iar and joy­ous.”</p>
    <p>She also took part in a newly launched ex­pe­ri­ence at Madame Tus­sauds called Be­hind The Magic where one can try out the work of a wax artist. Tay tried wax shap­ing, oil paint­ing and hair in­ser­tion.</p>
    <p>In a press re­lease for the event, the star says: “It was a great sur­prise that I ac­tu­ally could get my hands on a small bit of the process of mak­ing a wax fig­ure. It was un­real to see how hairs are ac­tu­ally in­serted, it was def­i­nitely an eye­open­ing ex­pe­ri­ence!”</p>
    <p>The Be­hind The Magic ex­pe­ri­ence can be booked on­line at Madame Tus­sauds’ web­site at: www.madame­tus­sauds.com/sin­ga­pore.</p>
    <p>Tay’s wax fig­ure is one of the per­ma­nent fig­ures at Madame Tus­sauds Sin­ga­pore along­side fig­ures of other prom­i­nent Sin­ga­pore­ans such as singers JJ Lin and Ste­fanie Sun, for­mer prime min­is­ter Lee Kuan Yew and his wife, film-maker Jack Neo and actor-host Gur­mit Singh as his iconic char­ac­ter Phua Chu Kang.</p>

